<P><center>
<H2>CBS/Turner: Pots v. Kettle<H2><br>
</CENTER>
<P>
<blockquote>


"Mike Wallace did a piece for the January 19th <I>60 Minutes</I> on the Ted Turner/Rupert Murdoch feud. 
<P>
"Murdoch wouldn't talk to him, so Andrew Neal (sp?), a former editor of one of Murdoch's London newspapers, served as the Murdoch expert. . . .
<P>
"Wallace: 'In the last election campaign Murdoch contributed more than a million and a half dollars to political candidates, most of them Republicans. . . . Which was obvious during the election campaign to readers of the [New York] <I>Post</I>. . . . And on Murdoch's new cable channel the news also comes with a conservative spin. . . . Ted Turner disdains all this. He believes Murdoch's political bias contaminates his news coverage.'
<P>
"Turner: '[Murdoch] looks down his nose at do-good, honest journalism. He thinks that his media should be used by him to further his own goals.' "
<P>
from the Media Research Center's <I>CyberAlert</I>, January 20, 1997


</blockquote>
