<DOCOLDNO>IA035-000699-B009-308</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.empower.org:80/nationalreview/outrage/011897out.html 204.71.237.79 19970210003708 text/html 3868
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 10-Feb-97 00:37:56 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 21-Jan-97 00:42:13 GMT
Content-length: 3684
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Outrage du Jour</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<img src="/nationalreview/images/outrage.gif" ALT="Outrage du Jour">
<br>
<br>


<HR width=50%> 
<!-----------------Townhall------------------------------>
<I>January 18, 1997</I></center>
<BR>
<BR>

<P><center>
<H2>Dr. Ebonics</H2><br>
</CENTER>
<P>
<blockquote>


"Students can explore the link between the languages of African peoples throughout the diaspora in a course called Ebonics. 
<P>
"Ebonics has been portrayed over the years as slang, a corruption of English, or a minor subdivision of the English language. The course, which was formerly called Black English, will present Ebonics positively in the spirit of Afrocentrism. <P>
" 'Ebonics is rooted in the African experience; it is the result of African languages that have come in contact with European languages over many centuries,' said Professor Aisha Blackshire-Belay, Ph.D.. <P>
" 'Students will look at writings from educators, researchers and linguists in a critical approach to the issues, facts and evidence pertaining to the language of African people in the attempt to fully grasp the debate and controversy of the subject matter,' said Blackshire-Belay. <P>
"The renovated course is being offered through the African-American Studies department. It will be taught by Blackshire-Belay, an African-American studies linguist. <P>
" 'The primary aim of this course,' said Blackshire-Belay, 'is to provide an Africological approach to the observation of the cultural-linguistic continuity of African people throughout the world.' 
"According to Blackshire-Belay, the Ebonics course will be taught from an Afrocentric perspective and with the 'view that it is a language in its own right.' <P>
"The course will teach language performance skills and analytical methods developed by Blackshire-Belay and other leading Ebonics linguists and researchers. <P>
"The class is a three-credit, graduate level course, but undergraduate seniors may be admitted with the professor's approval. <P>
"The class is not a requirement for African-American studies majors, but it is for graduate students who are working toward doctoral degrees in the area of Ebonics. Ebonics will be offered every year and is becoming a very popular class. Students outside the African-American studies program have expressed interest in the course. <P>
" 'If given the chance I would take the course,' said junior Renee Williamson, a mathematics major. 'It's an opportunity to learn more about your people.' <P>
" 'It sounds interesting; if I wasn't in such a hurry to graduate, I would take it,' said senior Georgina Texeira, a computer science major."
<P>

From the Temple University News, http://newsroom.temple.edu/issues/Archives/Spring96/feb8/news2.html
</blockquote>
<!------------------------------------------------------------>
<P>
