<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin"></center>
<br>
<br>


<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<b>Sexual Politics, 1997</b><br>
Reporters have been belatedly asking feminists why they're not supporting Paula Corbin Jones when they were so vehement in their support for Anita Hill. The subtext: Could it be that their stance on sexual harassment depends on the politics of the person being accused? The resulting squirming by feminists has been a delightful spectacle. According to today's <I>Washington Times</I>, feminist grande dame Betty Friedan explains that Mrs. Jones doesn't have a case because "she wasn't killed. She wasn't harassed [for her rejection of then-Gov. Clinton's alleged advances]. She wasn't fired. Her boss wasn't told to get rid of her." Mrs. Jones, Friedan explains, is a gold-digging bitch. Hmmm . . . sounds like blaming the victim to us. There's just one problem with Mrs. Friedan's attempted justification: It applies to Anita Hill too. Better go back to the drawing board. (That goes double for the woman who wrote in to the <I>New York Times</I> yesterday that Jones shouldn't be taken seriously because she waited until after Clinton was president to file charges. Hill waited for TEN YEARS, until Clarence Thomas had achieved prominence; Jones told friends about her alleged incident immediately and filed charges soon after her name appeared in print as a Clinton lover.) 
<P>
<b>The Language of Life</b><br>
Richard Cohen's column today notes that Fr. Richard John Neuhaus, editor of <I>First Things</I>, "is no marginal figure" because he is a "frequent contributor to <I>National Review</I>." We're flattered, we guess, but we wish Mr. Cohen's foray into the <I>First Things</I> controversy were not merely another tired lament about the "extremism" of anti-abortion rhetoric and how it encourages violence. Now <I>First Things</I>, of course, published a symposium in 1994 on why violence in the anti-abortion cause is wrong. But obviously no amount of such condemnations will satisfy pro-choicers. Nor is their concern really for civil debate: when's the last time the Cohens of this world spoke out against coat-hanger imagery, or the contemptible suggestion that men shouldn't be allowed to take a pro-life stand? No, what they want is for pro-lifers to stop making the allegedly dangerous claim that abortion takes a human life. The other side's rhetoricthat the fetus is just a bunch of protoplasm, for instancehas dangerous consequences too, as the Delaware infanticide case demonstrates. The difference is that the pro-abortion rhetoric is false.
<P>
<b>Truth in Labeling</b><br>
By the way, since the label "anti-choice"whose crudity takes the breath awayhas become more or less universal among apologists for feticide describing anti-abortionists, with no less than Al Gore using it in his NARAL address yesterday, isn't it about time we all started calling them pro-abortion?
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
