<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for January 21, 1997</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>Skeleton at The Feast</b><br>
D.C. has been absolutely inundated with Democrats this weekend. You couldn't spit without hitting one, and believe us, we frequently wanted to. . . . In a passage of his Inaugural address that's sure to escape much comment, President Clinton promised an America where the streets would be filled with the sound of children's laughter because nobody would be shooting them or trying to sell them drugs. If Clinton could actually accomplish these and sundry other feats he promised, we shouldn't have made him Presidenthe would already be God. Many, perhaps most people would respond to this criticism that the President was articulating a worthy ideal, and that's what ritual oratory is for. Perhaps. But an ideal is abstract, not concrete; a principle, not a situation. And ideals are meaningless without practical plans to approach them. The fact that saccharine such as the President today served is what Americans now expect from great political oratory is an indictment of the sensibilities of the day. 
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
