<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for January 18, 1997</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>The Further Adventures of Jacob Heilbrunn</b><br>
Jacob Heilbrunn, author of "Theocon v. Neocon" (the primary target of Ramesh Ponnuru's "Con Job" in <I>NR</I>'s latest issue) responds to some of his critics in the new edition of the <I>New Republic</I>. The response is characteristically poor. Having insisted without evidence in the original article that Catholic intellectuals like Fr. Richard John Neuhaus, Robert George, and Russell Hittinger are out to make America a "Christian nation" politically, he now allows that "perhaps" this was wrongwhile insinuating that it's not a very important point. Nor did he mean to suggest that Neuhaus was an anti-Semite. Oh no, he was just criticizing attempts to read Catholicism into the Constitution. Again, he has provided no evidence that anybody is doing that, for there is none. And if his point was narrowly constitutional, why the closing attack on Fr. Neuhaus's defense of the Southern Baptist resolution on converting Jews? We may have more to say on this at a later date. For now, we'll just note the obvious: having repeatedly lied <I>in</I> his article, Heilbrunn is now lying <I>about</I> his article. 
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
