<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>Washington Bulletin</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>


<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for January 16, 1997</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>Big MaxTax Attack</b><br>
In Tuesday's <I>Wall Street Journal</I>, Stephen Moore picks up on a brilliant idea of Alan Reynolds (full disclosureboth men are on <I>NR</I>'s masthead): the alternative maximum tax. Liberal attacks on tax reform have centered on the harm it would allegedly do to middle-class families by removing breaks and flattening rates. Why not deflect that attack by introducing a flat tax as an option for taxpayers? Anyone who wanted could pay taxes under the current system, itemizing all deductions. Or taxpayers could opt for a 25 per cent flat tax (minus a tax credit for payroll tax payments to prevent double taxation). Call it the MaxTax. In addition to its political advantages and intellectual elegance, the idea of injecting choice into the tax system would also offer significant policy advantages: the messy and complicated "transition issues" that have bedeviled technical analysts of the flat tax would disappear. Instead of having to phase out various deductions, a market-like system would make those deductions less and less relevant as taxpayers opted out. 
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P><P>

