HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 10-Feb-97 00:41:37 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 16-Jan-97 01:51:29 GMT
Content-length: 5092
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>Washington Bulletin</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>


<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for January 15, 1997</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>LibertarianismII</b><br>
The American Enterprise Institute hosted a panel discussion of Charles Murray's <I>What It Means to Be a Libertarian: A Personal Interpretation</I> Tuesday. Moderated by James Glassman, the panel included heavy-hitters Robert Bork, Irving Kristol, and Michael Novak. The discussion was fascinating, and entertaining: Novak read a poem comparing Charles Murray to dance king Arthur Murray, for instance. Kristol and Bork were the most critical. Bork focused on Murray's claim that individuals own themselves and its implications on drugs, pornography, and suicide. Kristol argued that Murray's rosy view of human nature overestimates the likelihood that harmonious communities will spontaneously form. So far, so arguable. Kristol's next points, however, seemed weaker. Against Murray's claim that freedom is necessary for "a fully human life," Kristol argued that in fact many voluntary surrenders of freedom (as in marriage) are necessary. Against the notion of self-ownership, Kristol said that we are all initial public offerings (IPOs), and would if lucky be oversubscribed: "No one owns himself, unless he is very unlucky." Lastly, he argued that communities can't exist without standards that would restrict libertyin some cases, through social sanctions fiercer than law. These arguments suffice to refute a Rousseauvianism that defines freedom, as it were, sociologically. ("Autonomy" is a better word for this concept, central to modern liberalism.) Against Murray's Burkean libertarianism, however, these arguments are beside the point, because he defines freedom as the absence of coercion strictly defined. Social sanctions may be on occasion more psychologically compelling than the use or threat of force embodied in the law, but the two are formally distinguishable for the purpose of moral analysis. Kristol is unquestionably righti.e., no one would question himwhen he says that communities have to shape character. But Murray's argument isn't about what functions must be performed in a society but about specifying which institutions should perform them. Kristol and Bork may be able to win that argumentwhen talk turned to concrete applications like local censorship regimes, they seemed to have Murray on the runbut first they have to engage it.
<P>
<b>Democrat Dreams</b><br>
E.J. Dionne's Monday column argues that a role reversal of sorts has taken place: liberals are just bursting with new ideas, while conservatives are the dispirited salesmen of "tired ideas." His evidence for the former claim: a conference last weekend with liberal thinkers Theda Skocpol, Stanley Greenberg, William Julius Wilson, and Alan Brinkley. Now it's true that liberals have shed the former complacency and grown more sophisticated in "trying to change the direction of the political debate" (Dionne), having learned from the Kristol family and other conservatives. But what's in the cupboard? Skocpol is quoted saying that two-parent families are ideal, while "single-parent families" are "second-best necessities." Greenberg argues that government programs , especially social-insurance programs, should be pitched to middle-class families. Brinkley says that big government has historically helped make America great. Wilson wants government to improve interracial unity by focusing on "problems" like "job security, wages, escalating medical and housing costs, public education, crime and drugs." None of these ideas is new. What's true in Skocpol's comments is trivial and obvious. Social democrats like Wilson have been arguing for a race-neutral panoply of new programs since the '60s. Greenberg's middle-class entitlement strategy dates back at least to the New Deal. Liberal historians and their readers have been making their arguments since time was. We don't have any particular enthusiasm for "new ideas," most of which turn out to be bad. But Dionne hasn't found any to worry about.
<P>
<b>On The Other Hand</b><br>
<I>The Washington Post</I> op-ed page does have at least one bright spot today: Henry Kissinger lays out a level-headed case for NATO expansion, and against making Russia a de facto member of the alliance. 
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
