<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - January 15, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 15, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

One of the most enduring qualities about Americans is that we
constantly strive to do better.  We did so this week when we 
finally recognized the heroism of seven black veterans of World War 
II with the Congressional Medal of Honor.

<p>

Now these men fought with valor in segregated units.  But for
a half-century they were denied the full recognition they deserved.

<p>

One of them was Vernon Joseph Baker, the sole survivor of those
honored this week.  In 1945, he intentionally drew enemy fire so 
his wounded men could be evacuated.  He recounted his experience 
to reporters saying, &quot;Men were being killed all around me, cut 
to pieces.  But I escaped without a scratch.  I knew there was someone 
on my shoulder.&quot;

<p>

This same faith, which saw Lt. Baker through the horrors of combat,
also saw him through difficult times in America's history.  Although 
saddened by the injustices he and other blacks faced, he said, 
&quot;I always knew things would get better, and I'm happy I'm here 
to see it.&quot;

<p>

Today we all share that joy as we remember their sacrifice.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

