<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - January 16, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 16, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

I'm afraid we've reached a dangerous point in American politics.
It seems that public scandals have replaced public policy as the top 
agenda item in Washington.

<p>

We're all familiar with the allegations against my friend Newt
Gingrich.  Now it seems that his accusers may have committed serious 
crimes in their efforts to discredit him.  The FBI is currently 
investigating how a private phone conversation between the Speaker 
and GOP leaders was illegally taped.  They're also looking
into the role of the Ethics Committee's senior Democrat, Jim McDermott, 
in leaking the tape to the media.

<p>

It's clear that neither political party has a monopoly on virtue
or vice.  But what's also clear is that this constant drumbeat of 
scandals is shifting the focus away from dealing with important 
problems we have to solve.  Who is going to defend the sanctity 
of life, promote reliable standards of right and wrong, and bring
relief to over-taxed families, while we're all confronting our leaders' 
latest ethical lapses?

<p>

It's time we got to the bottom of this mess and then move on
with the people's business.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

