<title>Daily Commentary - January 17, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 17, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

How ironic that just as we prepare to observe the memory of a
man who devoted his life to correcting injustices peacefully, some 
in our country try to do so violently.

<p>

If Dr. Martin Luther King were alive today, he no doubt would
join us in condemning yesterday's bombing in Atlanta.  We pro-lifers
are heartbroken by the deaths of millions of innocent children
through abortion.  But we must seek a peaceful solution to this
tragedy.  One that teaches the value of all human life.

<p>

Like Dr. King's struggle against segregation and racism, our
struggle against abortion is a process that involves changing 
hearts and minds. We will never win the hearts and minds of the 
American people through violence.  This movement is about life, 
not destruction.

<p>

Thankfully no lives were lost in the explosion.  And we look
forward to the day when no lives are lost inside the abortion clinic. 
We at the Family Research Council will take the lead in condemning 
these acts.  But we will also redouble our efforts to extend the 
protection of our laws to unborn children.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

