<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - February 5, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
February 5, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

In last night's State of the Union Address, Bill Clinton was
articulate as usual. He spoke with the concern we all share
for the problems facing our nation, and ticked off a list of government-backed
initiatives and programs to deal with them.

<p>

But as the president spoke, it struck me that shuffling taxpayer
dollars from one government account to another isn't going to
address the real problems we face.  After last year's speech I
said that politicians had not given adequate answers to the questions
gnawing at America's heart.  Well, after a year of election campaigns
we're right back where we started.

<p>

We still see our standard of living sag as our taxes rise.  Family
breakdown and poverty continue to damage our children.  The general
breakdown of values leaves us morally confused.  And illegal drugs
are flooding our neighborhoods and schools.

<p>

Now these problems won't be solved overnight.  But we haven't
made enough progress on them.  I hope this year is different and
that Washington finds a way to talk about the things that touch
on the hearts of the people.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008. 

<p>

