<title>January 22, 1996 Press Release</title>

<body>

<font size=-1>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
January 22, 1996<br>
CONTACT: Kristi S. Hamrick -- (202) 393-2100. For Radio: Kristin Hansen.<br>
For Soundbites: (202) 393-NEWS ext. 2
</font>

<p>

<center><h2>JUDGE TELLS PENTAGON<br>
IT MUST SELL SMUT</h2></center>

<p>

<b>WASHINGTON, D.C. --</b> Forcing the military to sell pornography
is &quot;a miscarriage of justice and another indicator of an
out-of-control judiciary,&quot; Family Research Council Military
Readiness Project Director Lt. Col. Robert Maginnis said about
the decision made Wednesday by a New York judge.

<p>

Judge Shira Scheidlin, U.S. District Court for the Southern District
of New York, said that the new law banning the sale of sexually
explicit material in military stores violates the pornographer's
First Amendment rights.

<p>

Colonel Maginnis explained, &quot;Congress has the constitutional
obligation (Art. I, Sec. 8) to set the rules and regulations for
the military.  The Congress passed the ban, and it was signed
by the President.  The law bans 'the sale or rental of sexually
explicit written or videotaped material on property under the
jurisdiction of the Department of Defense.' Although customers
pay less than the market price for pornography in military stores,
the Pentagon earns over $4 million in annual sales of 219 sexually
explicit magazines.

<p>

&quot;The major constitutional obligation in this area is for
Congress to protect the military's combat fitness, therefore it
has declared that selling pornography is bad for readiness.&quot;

<p>

The Pentagon has declared that it does not intend to appeal the
decision.  &quot;This is desertion in the face of pornographers,&quot;
said Maginnis.  &quot;The Pentagon is running from its duty to
execute the law and liberal judges are doing the dirty work.

<p>

&quot;A military that says it wants more servicewomen is at the
same time forced to remain one of the nation's largest purveyors
of pornography.  It has been shaken by the ongoing Aberdeen Proving
Grounds sexual harassment scandal.  News that the military must
continue selling woman-demeaning smut sends the wrong message
to traumatized women who understand the direct association between
exposure to pornography and sexual misconduct.&quot;

<p>

<center><h4>FOR MORE INFORMATION OR INTERVIEWS,<br>
CONTACT THE FRC MEDIA OFFICE AT (202) 393-2100.<br>
FOR SOUNDBITES, CALL (202) 393-NEWS ext. 2.</h4></center>

<p>

