<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>February 6, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>
<LI> A new-year welcome to the University of Chicago <I>Criterion</I>. The first issue (November 1996) includes article on campus affairs, book reviews, op-eds, a concert review, and not a single cheap shot or boring page. In its statement of purpose, the <I>Criterion</I> promises to "remain bound by civility and enlivened with good humor." It's off to a good start.
<P>
<LI> The eyes glaze over when politicos talk generalities about Big Government and Washington micro-management. But it is examples which enliven and persuade. Take these: 1) The U.S. National Park Service in December asked the Army Corps of Engineers and the U.S. Coast Guard to deny Wisconsin and Minnesota the permits needed to build a mile-long four-lane $60-million bridge over the St. Croix river. The Park Service says the bridge would "disrupt the natural flow of the river and destroy the natural scenery." Hundreds of thousands of dollars have already been spent relocating a colony of endangered mussels at the site to overcome a previous federal obstacle. 2)  The Environmental Protection Agency declared its opposition to the construction of a Western Bypass highway in northern Virginia, saying the road is unnecessary. The federal agency can stop the projectdeclared a high priority by the state of Virginia and entirely within Virginiaby withholding gas-tax money and saying that the road will "generate" traffic and worsen air quality. 3) The Federal Highway Administration is preparing formal rulemaking for the <I>Federal Register</I? establishing the types of state roads which must carry center line and edge line markings. Those poor dumb engineers in the state highway administrationsthey just can't be trusted to make sensible judgments about their own roads.
</blockquote>


<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
