<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 23, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>


<P> The media have taken an interest in the possible link between abortion and breast cancernow that someone has published a study debunking it. A Danish survey of over 1.5 million women, which found no connection between induced abortion and future incidence of breast cancer, has been heralded by the press as the definitive conclusion to the longstanding debate. Not so fast, warns Michael Fumento. Denmark's national abortion registry goes back only to 1973, and the risk of cancer increases with age. Thus, notes Fumento, "most of the women born late enough to have had their abortions registered are still too young to be at risk for breast cancer . . . [and] most old enough to be at risk of breast cancer were in their reproductive years before the abortion registry was begun." In other words, Dr. Joel Brind's analysis of 23 different studies, which suggests that abortion increases a woman's risk of developing breast cancer by 30 per cent, is still relevantif not to the press, then at least to pregnant young women.
<P>
<LI>   Mr. Fumento will be appearing as a guest on <I>NR Online</I> editor Chris Weinkopf's Internet radio show (<a href="http://www.grit.com">www.grit.com</a>), live, Thursday 1:15 to 1:45 p.m. EST. The interview will then be available, on demand, as of Friday morning. If you have any questions for Mr. Fumento, please e-mail them to <a href="mailto:chris@grit.com">chris@grit.com</a>.
</blockquote>


<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
