<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 15, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>


	


<LI>Feminists on the warpath over the alleged sexual abuse of female recruits at the Army's Aberdeen Proving Ground in Maryland want to use the scandal to advance the agenda of women in combat, much as they used the Navy's Tailhook scandal to achieve the integration of combat vessels. They should be asked to explain how isolated instances of the mistreatment of women in the military can be remedied by the wholesale abuse of women at the hands of enemy soldiers. Meanwhile, Congress should question the wisdom of co-ed basic training. The Reagan Administration ended a Carter-era experiment with co-ed basic training when it became clear that men were not being physically challenged and women were suffering a disproportionate number of injuries. The Marine Corps's way of doing things, where men and women go through basic training separately, appears to be beneficial to women, and Congressional Republicans ought to have the courage to say so. But only a few, including Rep. Bob Livingston, are willing to question sex integration in the military. Should Republicans be allowed to serve in combat?

</blockquote>


