<B><a href="/heritage/library/categories/education/bg1088.html">The Social Consequences of Choice: Why It Matters Where Poor Children Go To School,</a></B> <BR>
by Denis Doyle
<P>
Backgrounder, No. 1088, The Heritage Foudnation<HR>

<P>
Denis Doyle, Senior Fellow in Education at Heritage and author
of the study, reviews H.R. 3467, Saving Our Children:  The American
Community Renewal Act of 1996.  Title II of this provision would
implement an education choice scholarship program that includes
both private and religious schools in areas deemed to be &quot;renewal
communities.&quot; The proposed legislation would allow each locality
to determine the value of the special scholarships, with the maxiumum
value being no greater than the existing per-capita cost of education
in the local public school district. Doyle determines that this
legislation will enable poor children to enroll in better schools
and give their parents more choices concerning their education.
9 pp.  CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214
Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6058,
fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>, Internet <a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>.
<P>
<B>SUNY's Core Curricula: The Failure to Set Consistent &amp;
High Academic Standards</B>
<P>
Empire Foundation for Policy Research<HR>

<P>
In an attempt to discover why intellectual standards have fallen
and students' knowledge has declined in basic areas of education,
the New York Association of Scholars and the Empire Foundation
for Policy Research commissioned this study of the campuses of
the State University of New York. They discovered a nationwide
trend in whereby students take an odd mixture of courses that
do not build on previous knowledge, while avoiding more fundamental
and serious subjects. For example, one campus mandates that students
take courses in physical education while at the same time does
not require courses in history, literature, philosophy, arts,
English composition, mathematics or science. In addition, intellectual
permissiveness and political correctness are running rampant on
these campuses with courses such as, &quot;Literature of Sports,&quot;Deviance,&quot;
&quot;Love and Sexuality,&quot; and &quot;Stage Combat.&quot;
33 pp.  CONTACT: Empire Foundation, 130 Washington Avenue, Suite
1000, Albany, NY 12210, 518/383-2877, fax 518/432-6617.
<P>
<B>Charter Schools in Action: What Have We Learned?</B><br>
 by Chester Finn, Bruno Manno, and Louann Bierlein
<P>
Hudson Institute<HR>

<P>
Finn, Manno and Bierlein report their findings from the first
year of a two-year Hudson Institute study of U.S. charter schools.
The report focuses on the schools' start-up problems, solutions
to those problems, and the policy environments in which such schools
are most apt to thrive or falter. Start-up problems, not surprisingly,
include financial burdens and regulatory and political hurdles.
Among the many recommendations the writers make are setting up
charter schools to be legal entities in their own right, giving
charter schools the same per pupil operating funds that conventional
public schools receive, and using the charter model to develop
ways of holding all public schools accountable for their results.
Hudson suggests that charter schools may be the most vibrant force
in American education today and notes that the current demand
for charter schools far outweighs the supply. 127 pp.  CONTACT:
Hudson Institute, Herman Kahn Center, P.O. Box 26-919, Indianapolis,
IN  46226, 317/545-1000, 317/545-9639, Internet <a href="http://www.hudson.org/hudson/">http://www.hudson.org/hudson/</a>
<P>
<B>Education Reform 1995-1996,</B><br>
 by Chester Finn and Diane Ravitch
<P>
Hudson Institute<HR>

<P>
In the third annual report card on the progress of education reform
in the United States, the nation once again earned a grade of
&quot;C.&quot; The purpose of this report is to evaluate major
developments on several key refom fronts including course-taking,
achievement, standards, reinventing education, instruction, and
reinventing the federal role in education. Finn and Ravitch discover
rising enrollment figues in advanced math and science courses,
but disappointedly find that while more than three-fifths of high
school graduates now proceed directly to college, barely two-fifths
of them were in the academic track in high school. The study recommends
that schools continue to try to adhere to the strong academic
core that the National Commission on Excellence suggests. 66 pp.
 CONTACT: Hudson Institute, Herman Kahn Center, P.O. Box 26-919,
Indianapolis, IN  46226, 317/545-1000, 317/545-9639, Internet
